commit.message:
Set up rules for inferring the result type of builtin numeric binary operations.

See https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/4237
Add an assertion to a type analysis function to make sure that we the "same type" case has been handled before.

Replace "coerce_to_integer()" (which coerced the node to a C long) by a more appropriate "coerce_to_size()" that coerces to Py_ssize_t. All usages actually wanted that.

Closes https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/5743
Make sure that we correctly coerce a sequence multiplier ("[...] * n") to 'Py_ssize_t' if it's a Python 'int'. Otherwise, we can't call PySequence_Multiply() with it.
Include the case of a binary operation with the same builtin types on both sides, which usually returns the same type again.
Fix type inference for (true-)division (actually inferring "C double" for integer "/") and test type inference in for both language_level=2/3.
Add a safety check in the "type_inference_ll2.pyx" test that it really detects language_level=2.

milestone.description: Remove support for Python 2 and Python < 3.8.

title: Infer the result type of builtin numeric binary operations
